<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[264,1322,283,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,384,283,309]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Closest in appearance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evenhuis" authorityYear="2005" box="[692,789,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Adachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[692,789,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Adachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Hardy &amp; Kohn" authorityYear="1964" box="[846,1005,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Eurynogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[846,1005,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Eurynogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but easily separated by the disproportionately large mouthparts (
<figureCitation box="[711,784,324,350]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1578,1602]" captionTargetBox="[339,1236,1118,1567]" captionTargetId="figure-320@6.[296,1304,1109,1587]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Sympycnine and hydrophorine heads, diagrammatic frontal views. 1. Sigmatineurum napali Evenhuis. 2. Arciellia dolichostoma (Hardy &amp; Kohn) showing enlarged mouthparts. 3. Eurynogaster clavaticauda Van Duzee." pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) (mouthparts small and less conspicuous in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evenhuis" authorityYear="2005" box="[264,361,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Adachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,361,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Adachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Hardy &amp; Kohn" authorityYear="1964" box="[426,585,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Eurynogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[426,585,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Eurynogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and the hypopygium with a shovel­shaped cercus, and the hypandrium with a sharp, tricornate lateral process (
<figureCitation box="[873,961,404,430]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–24" captionStartId="15.[264,382,1428,1452]" captionTargetBox="[299,1296,654,1388]" captionTargetId="figure-250@15.[289,1297,646,1404]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 21–24. Hypopygia. 21. Adachia apicenigra (Van Duzee). 22. Arciellia dolichostoma (Hardy &amp; Kohn). 23. Elmoia hamata (Hardy &amp; Kohn). 24. Eurynogaster angusticercus (Hardy &amp; Kohn). Abbreviations: bv = basiventral epandrial lobe; ce = cercus; hy = hypandrium; lh = lateral process of hypandrium; pg = postgonite; su = surstylus." pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
